{{distinguish|Bongo language (Indonesia)}} {{Infobox language |name=Bongo |states=[[South Sudan]] |ethnicity=[[Bongo people (South Sudan)|Bongo people]] |speakers={{sigfig|10,100|3}} |date=2000 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=[[Central Sudanic languages|Central Sudanic]] |fam3=[[Bongo–Bagirmi languages|Bongo–Bagirmi]] |fam4=[[Bongo–Baka languages|Bongo–Baka]] |iso3=bot |glotto=bong1285 |glottorefname=Bongo }}
'''Bongo''' (Bungu), also known as ''Dor'', is a [[Central Sudanic language]] spoken by the [[Bongo people (South Sudan)|Bongo people]] in sparsely populated areas of [[Bahr el Ghazal (region of South Sudan)|Bahr al Ghazal]] in South Sudan.
== Tone == Bongo is [[Tonal languages|tonal language]] that has the high (á), mid (ā), low (à) and falling (â) tones.
All falling tones occur on either long vowels or on vowel clusters or [[Semivowel|glides]]. When the tonal fall is not due to a preceding high tone, it can be indicated by a high tine followed by a low tone
{|align=center=1 cellpadding="5" class="wikitable" |- ! Ton || Example || Translation |- ||high ||{{IPA|bʊ́}} || ''hungry'' |- ||low ||{{IPA|tɪ̀ɪ̀}} || ''Pounded sesame'' |- ||falling || {{IPA|tââ}} /táà/ || ''when'' |}
==Numerals== Bongo has a [[quinary]]-[[vigesimal]] numeral system.<ref>[http://lingweb.eva.mpg.de/numeral/ Bongo at Numeral Systems of the World's Languages] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421165028/http://lingweb.eva.mpg.de/numeral/ |date=2014-04-21 }}</ref>
