{{Use Indian English|date=August 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox university |name = Central Institute of Higher Tibetan Studies |former_name = Central University for Tibetan Studies |image_name = Central University for Tibetan Studies logo.png |established = 1967 |chancellor = |city = [[Sarnath]], [[Varanasi]] |state = [[Uttar Pradesh]] |country = [[India]] |campus = |affiliations = |type = |website = {{url|http://www.cuts.ac.in/}} }}
The '''Central Institute of Higher Tibetan Studies''' ('''CIHTS'''; {{Bo|t=ཝ་ཎ་མཐོ་སློབ|w=wa Na mtho slob}}), formerly called '''Central University for Tibetan Studies''' ('''CUTS'''), is a [[Deemed University]] founded in [[Sarnath]], [[Varanasi]], [[India]], in 1967, as an autonomous organisation under Union [[Ministry of Culture (India)|Ministry of Culture]].<ref name=UGC>{{cite web|title=Deemed Universities|url=http://www.ugc.ac.in/inside/deemed%20universities/highertibetanstudies.html|work=Deemed Universities|publisher=UGC|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> The CIHTS was founded by Pt. [[Jawahar Lal Nehru]] in consultation with [[Tenzin Gyatso]], the [[Dalai Lama|Dalai of Lama]], with the aim of educating Tibetan youths in exile and Himalayan border students as well as with the aim of retranslating into Sanskrit and translating into Hindi and other modern Indian languages lost Indo-Buddhist Sanskrit texts that now exist only in Tibetan.<ref name=MoC>{{cite book|author=Department of Culture, India |title=Indian culture : tradition & continuity |year=2002|publisher=Department of Culture, Ministry of Tourism and Culture, Government of India |location=New Delhi |isbn=9788187614081 |page=13 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9vptAAAAMAAJ&q |edition=1st}}</ref>
Originally it functioned as a special constituent wing of [[Sampurnanand Sanskrit University]], Varanasi. In the early 1970s the [[Government of India]] reviewed the progress of the institute and decided to accord it a status of an autonomous body under the Department of Culture, Ministry of Education, Government of India in 1977 with 100% financial support from the Indian government.
The institute steadily progressed and the Indian government declared it a [[Deemed University]] on 5 April 1988. Formerly headed by the like of Kyabje Zong Rinpoche, Samdong Rinpoche (former Prime Minister of the Central Tibetan Administrations), and [[Ngawang Samten]], also a former alumnus, the institute is headed by Lobsang Norbu Shastri.<ref name="VC's Message">{{cite web | url=http://www.cuts.ac.in/GuestSection/vc_desk.html | title=VC's Message | publisher=CUTS | date=2016 | accessdate=February 14, 2016}}</ref> Assisted by faculty members, with the goal of achieving excellence in the fields of [[Tibetology]] and [[Buddhology]]. The university attracts a large number{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=September 2016}} of students from many regions of the Himalayan family, with students coming from Kinnaur, Lahaul, Spiti, Ladakh, Monpas from Arunachal. Students from Nepal consist of students, from Sherpas, Lamas and many more from the bordering regions of Mustang and Dolpo. Other than these, students also come from Bhutan and Mongolia.
The university also offers courses in Tibetan medicine (Sowa Rigpa), Astrology and Fine Arts.
On 14 January 2009 the institute was officially declared as a university and the inauguration was made by the XIV Dalai Lama. Now the name of the university is Central University of Tibetan Studies.
