{{Infobox language |name=Hausa Sign Language |altname=Kano Sign Language |states=[[Nigeria]] |region=[[Kano]] |speakers=?<!--no speaker numbers in the Ethnologue 18--> |familycolor=sign |family=[[Deaf-community sign language]] |iso3=hsl |glotto=haus1246 |glottorefname=Hausa Sign Language }}
'''Hausa Sign Language''' (''Maganar Hannu'') is the indigenous [[sign language]] of the [[Deaf community]] in [[Hausa language|Hausa]]-speaking city of [[Kano]] in northern Nigeria. Estimates as to the number of signers using this language "vary greatly, from 70,000 to five million".<ref>Schmaling, Constanze. 2015. ''Sign Languages of the World: A Comparative Handbook'', Julie Bakken Jepsen, Goedele De Clerck, Sam Lutalo-Kiingi, William B. McGregor, (eds.), 362-390. Berlin: Walter de Gruyter.</ref>
